Despite a number of complex and even chilling signals, the new
president will inherit the stable economy that his predecessor achieved but=
 could never articulate=E2=80=94Trump=E2=80=99s latest stroke of luck in a =
lifetime of unprecedented good fortune.

William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F19%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%281%2F19%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F19%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%281%2F19%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Wall Street is gearing up for a big year in investment banking.
The six largest U.S. banks generated $36 billion in profits in the fourth q=
uarter of 2024, more than double what they made during the same period in 2=
023. For the full year, these banks generated a net income of $146 billion,=
 led by Jamie Dimon=E2=80=99s powerhouse, with net earnings of $54 billion.=
 For JPMorgan Chase, Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, Wells Fargo, Citigroup,=
 and Bank of America, that appears to be the amuse-bouche before another ex=
pected earnings feast in 2025.
Can anything ruin the party?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Maybe. We are long overdue for a correction, given that financial crises hi=
storically come once every 20 years or so, and there is at least one warnin=
g beacon flashing in the bond market. Since September, the Federal Reserve =
has effectively lowered short-term interest rates by 100 basis points. At t=
he same time, the yield on 10-year Treasuries=E2=80=94supposedly among
the safest debt instruments=E2=80=94has gone in the opposite direction, ris=
ing over 100 bips and worrying the heck out of many market observers. Mortg=
age rates have also moved up swiftly, despite the Fed=E2=80=99s cuts. The a=
verage rate on a 30-year fixed mortgage is back over 7 percent for the firs=
t time since 2023.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

At first blush, it=E2=80=99s all a bit confusing. How could long-term inter=
est rates be going up
when the Fed has been lowering short-term interest rates? Last September, f=
or instance, the yield on the 10-year Treasury was around 3.6 percent. Toda=
y it is nearly 4.7 percent=E2=80=94a 30 percent increase in four months. Th=
at=E2=80=99s a significant leap, as far as these things go. Charlie Gaspari=
no, the Fox Business analyst and friend of the house, tweeted that the risi=
ng yields =E2=80=9Cshould have every stock investor worried about a signifi=
cant selloff.=E2=80=9D And no less an observer
than Larry Summers, the celebrity economist and former treasury secretary, =
tweeted on Tuesday that the rising Treasury yields =E2=80=9Cconfirms concer=
ns about looming budget deficits and a rising neutral rate.=E2=80=9D (As al=
ways, this is not investment advice.)

=C2=A0

Anxious to figure out what the heck is going on in the bond market, and wha=
t it might be signaling for the financial markets overall, I rang up
Lotfi Karoui, the chief credit strategist in Goldman Sachs=E2=80=99 researc=
h department. His message was both fascinating and reassuring. He said that=
 intermediate and long-term yields were =E2=80=9Ca lot more sensitive=E2=80=
=9D to =E2=80=9Cgrowth and inflation expectations=E2=80=9D than to the Fed=
=E2=80=99s short-term interest-rate policy actions. During the past six mon=
ths, more or less since the Fed started lowering interest rates, there has =
been a growing consensus that the Biden
administration=E2=80=99s attempts to engineer a so-called soft landing for =
the economy had actually succeeded=E2=80=94and that, as Karoui put it, =E2=
=80=9Cthe durability of the cycle is a lot stronger than most people had in=
itially envisioned.=E2=80=9D

In short, interestingly, the growing confidence that the economy will not s=
lip into an imminent recession is driving intermediate and long-term intere=
st rates higher. Karoui acknowledged that corporations are focused on these=
=C2=A0 intermediate and longer-term rate
moves=E2=80=94including the spread over Treasuries=E2=80=94rather than the =
quotidian short-term moves orchestrated by the Fed, when it comes to their =
borrowing plans. =E2=80=9CThis is probably as good as it gets in terms of a=
 level of borrowing costs,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CBottom line, there=E2=
=80=99s a lot of moving components here. There=E2=80=99s a spread component=
 for the borrowers outside of the government, and then there=E2=80=99s inte=
rmediate long-dated yields. And that=E2=80=99s really a reflection of growt=
h and inflation expectations.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

Lotfi Expectations
------------------

The yields, Karoui explained, have been moving up because of the
consensus that the economy is performing well and will continue to do so, a=
nd because once-rampant inflation is being reined in. =E2=80=9CSpreads are =
just a reflection of the general state of the economy,=E2=80=9D he continue=
d. =E2=80=9CAt the moment, things are pretty good.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Long-term bond investors, however, are taking duration risk by making a bet=
 on where interest rates will be in the future, in Karoui=E2=80=99s view. I=
ndeed, if
long-term bond yields move up, then the price of their bonds will move down=
, since bond prices move in an inverse relationship to yields. =E2=80=9CTha=
t risk,=E2=80=9D he continued, =E2=80=9Cbasically is a reflection of the le=
vel of real G.D.P. growth and inflation. And so when you have an accelerati=
on in real G.D.P. growth, the cost of capital is supposed to go up. And the=
 one thing that initiates that process is essentially the level of the risk=
-free rate. And so, very simplistically, five- and 10-year yields are
essentially a function of long-term growth and inflation expectations, and =
the firmer they are, the higher they move.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Of course, if interest rates continue to move up, that could have the count=
erproductive effect of raising the cost of capital beyond borrowers=E2=80=
=99 comfort levels. That=E2=80=99s what happened during the 2008 financial =
crisis, and the 2020 pandemic, before the Fed took control and flooded the
zone with cheap money. Nevertheless, Karoui said that we are much closer to=
 achieving the Fed=E2=80=99s two-pronged employment and inflation mandates =
than many observers thought possible. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve made quite a l=
ot of progress,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThe labor market is rebalanced. =
Price inflation has declined. There=E2=80=99s still another leg lower to ac=
hieve, but there isn=E2=80=99t nearly the same emergency to attacking polic=
y rates that we had a year ago.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

With the goals of the dual mandate in sight, I wondered, where does the Fed=
 go from here? Per Karoui, the market is pricing in =E2=80=9Ca little over =
one [interest-rate] cut=E2=80=9D over the next 24 months. At Goldman, thoug=
h, he said the expectation remains that the Fed ends up =E2=80=9Cdelivering=
 three cuts=E2=80=9D over the next 18 months. But he cautioned that expecta=
tions change on a daily basis. =E2=80=9CThe market basically is telling you=
 that they=E2=80=99re not quite done, but they=E2=80=99re close [to
being done],=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s the $1 million quest=
ion: Where is the terminal value of Fed Funds rates in this cycle?=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

But if the economy is performing better than expected=E2=80=94and it appear=
s that it will continue to do so in the near term=E2=80=94why are so many s=
mart people worrying about the rise in interest rates and the potential eff=
ect on the broader financial markets, including equities? Karoui said the r=
apid increase in
Treasury yields often has the effect of spooking investors in riskier asset=
s, such as stocks. =E2=80=9CGenerally, risk assets have a very tough time d=
igesting those types of moves, irrespective of what=E2=80=99s driving it,=
=E2=80=9D he said. And given that the equity markets are already at or near=
 all-time highs, and =E2=80=9Cvaluations are very expensive,=E2=80=9D the m=
argin for error is quite narrow. =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re walking a very tig=
ht rope,=E2=80=9D he continued. =E2=80=9CYou don=E2=80=99t have a lot of ro=
om for error here, and your sensitivity to small shocks
becomes a lot higher. And so that=E2=80=99s exactly why we=E2=80=99ve had t=
his sort of rocky start to the year in the equity market.=E2=80=9D

Naturally, Karoui expressed concern about the effect Trump II will have on =
tariffs and immigration=E2=80=94not to mention the impact that extending th=
e 2017 Trump tax cuts will have on deficits and the national debt level. =
=E2=80=9CWe have a 6.5, 7 percent budget deficit and an economy that=E2=80=
=99s at full employment,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s something =
that investors are focused on.
But has it really translated into a driver of bond yields? Not yet.=E2=80=
=9D Either way, it=E2=80=99s clear that the president will inherit the stab=
le economy that his predecessor achieved but could never articulate=E2=80=
=94Trump=E2=80=99s latest stroke of dumb luck in a lifetime brimming with u=
nprecedented good fortune.

