in exchange for her silence about the affair=E2=80=94a confidentiality agre=
ement that she violated after receiving her first $9 million over six years=
, in March 2021, in a series of tweets that claimed he had =E2=80=9Csexuall=
y harassed
and abused=E2=80=9D her.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">At the time, Leon claime=
d that she tried to extort him over their longtime, consensual affair, and =
that he paid her to make it all go away. She then sued him for defamation, =
intentional infliction of emotional distress, and gender-based violence. Bu=
t last week, in a 4-1 ruling, the Appellate Division in Manhattan rejected =
Ganieva=E2=80=99s appeal, arguing that the confidentiality agreement
she signed was pretty much ironclad, especially after she took the first $9=
 million. =E2=80=9CWe recognize the trauma attendant upon sexual abuse,=E2=
=80=9D the majority wrote. =E2=80=9CHowever, we disagree with the dissent t=
hat the same principle should allow plaintiff to repudiate a contractual ar=
rangement after accepting its benefits for over five years.=E2=80=9D<br/><b=
r/><strong>Susan Estrich</strong>, an attorney for Leon, told me in a state=
ment, =E2=80=9CThe appellate court=E2=80=99s ruling, which is a wholesale r=
ejection of Ms. Ganieva=E2=80=99s
arguments, upholds the trial court=E2=80=99s ruling and makes clear this su=
it brought by the Wigdor firm should never have been filed. The decision vi=
ndicates Mr. Black completely. He is pleased by the decision and will not s=
top his fight against the despicable lies the Wigdor firm has spread in its=
 irrational vendetta against him.=E2=80=9D (<em>Nota bene</em>: Ganieva was=
 represented by attorney <strong>Stephen Bergstein</strong> in the appeal, =
not Wigdor. She can appeal Thursday=E2=80=99s ruling to the state=E2=80=99s
highest judicial body, the Court of Appeals.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Leon also=
 won several procedural and substantive victories in his defense of a separ=
ate federal case, also brought by Wigdor, on behalf of a young autistic wom=
an known only as =E2=80=9CJane Doe.=E2=80=9D According to the suit, Doe cla=
imed Leon raped her in 2002, when she was 16, in Epstein=E2=80=99s Upper Ea=
st Side mansion. Leon, who hired Epstein to advise him on estate planning a=
nd
many other financial matters, has denied all the allegations and said that =
he has never even met the woman. Leon=E2=80=99s legal team subsequently tra=
cked down Doe=E2=80=99s family, including her mother, who told Leon=E2=80=
=99s investigators that the whole thing was a fabrication. Among their disc=
overies, according to court filings, was that Jane Doe did not have autism,=
 but rather had been diagnosed with borderline personality disorder. Leon=
=E2=80=99s team argued that Jane Doe studied people with autism and adopted=
 their
behaviors, and that her family members claimed she =E2=80=9Cused a series o=
f different names and personas [and] has a history of making up alternate r=
ealities.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In her multipart ruling on Thu=
rsday, District Court Judge <strong>Jessica</strong> <strong>Clarke</strong=
> seemed to agree with Leon=E2=80=99s attorneys=E2=80=99 argument that the =
woman was not of sound mind, and that Wigdor had a duty to not bring a case=
 that was
without merit. (Instead, Wigdor doubled down on the case by trying to amend=
 it with even more outrageous claims against Leon.) Wigdor will have a mont=
h to respond to a separate defense motion to be filed in a month that likel=
y will seek to dismiss the case entirely=E2=80=94and then Judge Clarke will=
 rule.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">You will recall from one of my previous missives=
 that Estrich was also trying to get Judge Clarke to give her
and Leon access to discovery=E2=80=94documents, testimony transcripts, depo=
sitions, etcetera=E2=80=94from yet another federal case. This one, in front=
 of Judge <strong>Jed Rakoff</strong>, is attempting to determine whether =
=E2=80=9CJane Doe,=E2=80=9D who received millions of dollars from the $290 =
million JPMorgan Chase fund for Epstein=E2=80=99s victims, should be forced=
 to return the money. Needless to say, such a request from one federal judg=
e to another regarding discovery materials would be highly unusual. But on =
Thursday, Judge
Clarke ruled that Leon=E2=80=99s defense team <em>could</em> access those m=
aterials. Another big victory for Leon.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Meanwhile, Leon=
 is also pursuing a malicious prosecution lawsuit against Wigdor, which he =
filed in August 2023, and which survived a motion to dismiss in September 2=
024. That case is now before the Appellate Division in New York State Court=
=2E Meanwhile, he remains Apollo=E2=80=99s largest shareholder, although
he is no longer involved with the company. Instead, he is focused on his ow=
n family office, Elysium Management=E2=80=94which, by the way, is <em>not</=
em> financing <strong>David Efune</strong>=E2=80=99s bid for <em>The Telegr=
aph</em>, as has been widely exaggerated in the British press.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><em>Now, =
for the main event=E2=80=A6</em></p></div>
