px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Wall Street is gearing up for a big year i=
n investment banking.
The six largest U.S. banks generated $36 billion in profits in the fourth q=
uarter of 2024, more than double what they made during the same period in 2=
023. For the full year, these banks generated a net income of $146 billion,=
 led by <strong>Jamie Dimon</strong>=E2=80=99s powerhouse, with net earning=
s of $54 billion. For JPMorgan Chase, Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, Wells =
Fargo, Citigroup, and Bank of America, that appears to be the <em>amuse-bou=
che</em> before another expected earnings feast in 2025.
Can anything ruin the party?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Maybe. We are long o=
verdue for a <em>correction</em>, given that financial crises historically =
come once every 20 years or so, and there is at least one warning beacon fl=
ashing in the bond market. Since September, the Federal Reserve has effecti=
vely lowered short-term interest rates by 100 basis points. At the same tim=
e, the yield on 10-year Treasuries=E2=80=94supposedly among
the safest debt instruments=E2=80=94has gone in the opposite direction, <em=
>rising</em> over 100 bips and worrying the heck out of many market observe=
rs. Mortgage rates have also moved up swiftly, despite the Fed=E2=80=99s cu=
ts. The average rate on a 30-year fixed mortgage is back over 7 percent for=
 the first time since 2023.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">At first blush, it=E2=
=80=99s all a bit confusing. How could long-term interest rates be going up
when the Fed has been lowering short-term interest rates? Last September, f=
or instance, the yield on the 10-year Treasury was around 3.6 percent. Toda=
y it is nearly 4.7 percent=E2=80=94a 30 percent increase in four months. Th=
at=E2=80=99s a significant leap, as far as these things go. <strong>Charlie=
</strong> <strong>Gasparino</strong>, the Fox Business analyst and friend o=
f the house, tweeted that the rising yields =E2=80=9Cshould have every stoc=
k investor worried about a significant selloff.=E2=80=9D And no less an obs=
erver
than <strong>Larry</strong> <strong>Summers</strong>, the celebrity economi=
st and former treasury secretary, tweeted on Tuesday that the rising Treasu=
ry yields =E2=80=9Cconfirms concerns about looming budget deficits and a ri=
sing neutral rate.=E2=80=9D (As always, this is not investment advice.)</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">A=
nxious to figure out what the heck is going on in the bond market, and what=
 it might be signaling for the financial markets overall, I rang up
<strong>Lotfi</strong> <strong>Karoui</strong>, the chief credit strategist=
 in Goldman Sachs=E2=80=99 research department. His message was both fascin=
ating and reassuring. He said that intermediate and long-term yields were =
=E2=80=9Ca lot more sensitive=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cgrowth and inflation exp=
ectations=E2=80=9D than to the Fed=E2=80=99s short-term interest-rate polic=
y actions. During the past six months, more or less since the Fed started l=
owering interest rates, there has been a growing consensus that the <strong=
>Biden</strong>
administration=E2=80=99s attempts to engineer a so-called soft landing for =
the economy had actually succeeded=E2=80=94and that, as Karoui put it, =E2=
=80=9Cthe durability of the cycle is a lot stronger than most people had in=
itially envisioned.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>In short, interestingly, the growing=
 confidence that the economy will not slip into an imminent recession is dr=
iving intermediate and long-term interest rates higher. Karoui acknowledged=
 that corporations are focused on these=C2=A0 intermediate and longer-term =
rate
moves=E2=80=94including the spread over Treasuries=E2=80=94rather than the =
quotidian short-term moves orchestrated by the Fed, when it comes to their =
borrowing plans. =E2=80=9CThis is probably as good as it gets in terms of a=
 level of borrowing costs,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CBottom line, there=E2=
=80=99s a lot of moving components here. There=E2=80=99s a spread component=
 for the borrowers outside of the government, and then there=E2=80=99s inte=
rmediate long-dated yields. And that=E2=80=99s really a reflection of growt=
h and inflation expectations.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></div>
