<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The yields, Karoui explained, have been moving =
up because of the
consensus that the economy is performing well and will continue to do so, a=
nd because once-rampant inflation is being reined in. =E2=80=9CSpreads are =
just a reflection of the general state of the economy,=E2=80=9D he continue=
d. =E2=80=9CAt the moment, things are pretty good.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">Long-term bond investors, however, are taking duration risk by making =
a bet on where interest rates will be in the future, in Karoui=E2=80=99s vi=
ew. Indeed, if
long-term bond yields move up, then the price of their bonds will move down=
, since bond prices move in an inverse relationship to yields. =E2=80=9CTha=
t risk,=E2=80=9D he continued, =E2=80=9Cbasically is a reflection of the le=
vel of real G.D.P. growth and inflation. And so when you have an accelerati=
on in real G.D.P. growth, the cost of capital is supposed to go up. And the=
 one thing that initiates that process is essentially the level of the risk=
-free rate. And so, very simplistically, five- and 10-year yields are
essentially a function of long-term growth and inflation expectations, and =
the firmer they are, the higher they move.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">Of course, if interest rates continue to move up, that could have the co=
unterproductive effect of raising the cost of capital beyond borrowers=E2=
=80=99 comfort levels. That=E2=80=99s what happened during the 2008 financi=
al crisis, and the 2020 pandemic, before the Fed took control and flooded t=
he
zone with cheap money. Nevertheless, Karoui said that we are much closer to=
 achieving the Fed=E2=80=99s two-pronged employment and inflation mandates =
than many observers thought possible. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve made quite a l=
ot of progress,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThe labor market is rebalanced. =
Price inflation has declined. There=E2=80=99s still another leg lower to ac=
hieve, but there isn=E2=80=99t nearly the same emergency to attacking polic=
y rates that we had a year ago.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">With the=
 goals of the dual mandate in sight, I wondered, where does the Fed go from=
 here? Per Karoui, the market is pricing in =E2=80=9Ca little over one [int=
erest-rate] cut=E2=80=9D over the next 24 months. At Goldman, though, he sa=
id the expectation remains that the Fed ends up =E2=80=9Cdelivering three c=
uts=E2=80=9D over the next 18 months. But he cautioned that expectations ch=
ange on a daily basis. =E2=80=9CThe market basically is telling you that th=
ey=E2=80=99re not quite done, but they=E2=80=99re close [to
being done],=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s the $1 million quest=
ion: Where is the terminal value of Fed Funds rates in this cycle?=E2=80=9D=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;">But if the economy is performing better than expected=E2=80=94and it app=
ears that it will continue to do so in the near term=E2=80=94why are so man=
y smart people worrying about the rise in interest rates and the potential =
effect on the broader financial markets, including equities? Karoui said th=
e rapid increase in
Treasury yields often has the effect of spooking investors in riskier asset=
s, such as stocks. =E2=80=9CGenerally, risk assets have a very tough time d=
igesting those types of moves, irrespective of what=E2=80=99s driving it,=
=E2=80=9D he said. And given that the equity markets are already at or near=
 all-time highs, and =E2=80=9Cvaluations are very expensive,=E2=80=9D the m=
argin for error is quite narrow. =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re walking a very tig=
ht rope,=E2=80=9D he continued. =E2=80=9CYou don=E2=80=99t have a lot of ro=
om for error here, and your sensitivity to small shocks
becomes a lot higher. And so that=E2=80=99s exactly why we=E2=80=99ve had t=
his sort of rocky start to the year in the equity market.=E2=80=9D <br/><br=
/>Naturally, Karoui expressed concern about the effect <strong>Trump</stron=
g> II will have on tariffs and immigration=E2=80=94not to mention the impac=
t that extending the 2017 Trump tax cuts will have on deficits and the nati=
onal debt level. =E2=80=9CWe have a 6.5, 7 percent budget deficit and an ec=
onomy that=E2=80=99s at full employment,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s something that investors are focused on.
But has it really translated into a driver of bond yields? Not yet.=E2=80=
=9D Either way, it=E2=80=99s clear that the president will inherit the stab=
le economy that his predecessor achieved but could never articulate=E2=80=
=94Trump=E2=80=99s latest stroke of dumb luck in a lifetime brimming with u=
nprecedented good fortune.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
